Today was a great day. After school I went to the mall to buy chocolates from See's Candies, and glasses, and new pants from Guess? The salesguy who helped me out looked  like Collin Farrel. Take a slightly younger Collin. Same brows, nose, mouth, eyes, eyes, eyes. Guessorize him with crazy metro style. And ad congeniality. And you have the imaginary Collin Farrel brother. Except for this was a real person.

When I got back eventually I had a cool little art session with Kristine, Kelly, and Mia (age 3), all under the age of 10. We took some of my extra little box containers and painted them wickedlycolourfulcool. I get such a blast out of teaching kids art. Hmmm.... maybe I should be an art docent....what a crazy idea that would be...So yeah, it was cool. I also started them with bead necklaces, but after the boxes it was time to eat! Lubia Polo! My favorite food!!!! It's an Iranian dish that I just devour. Anyways, then I watched my little cousin Elijah (about 1 1/2 years) by the pool. Somehow it became 9ish and we were all outside and I was teaching Kristine and Kelly how to kick the ball properly. I kicked off my flip-flops, so my feet got totally blackened by the pavement. Me and Bij rode around the street in my old bike and his scooter. Speaking of bikes, the song Bicycle by Pink Floyd was mentioned in a convo about Pink Floyd b/w me, Eric, and Lisa today. Oh, the sprinkers had also gone off earlier on our boxes since we laid them out in the grass! But miraculously, they stayed okay for the most part!

So we went inside after being outside ((what goes up must come down!)) and we signed our boxes, and I washed my feet, and set up the game Operation for them, and got ready for bed. And am talking to Chelsea, and planning on getting up early tomorrow.

Look at Howlin Pele up there. How good-looking is he?

While I'm in class, I am so jittery. because I need to go outside and run. Pent up energy is like staring at a glass of water when you're thirsty, and not being able to drink it.

As the novel progresses, we begin to perceive that Holden's alienation is his way of protecting himself. Just as he wears his hunting hat to advertise his uniqueness, he uses his isolation as proof that he is better than everyone else around him and therefore above interacting with them. The truth is that interactions with other people usually confuse and overwhelm him, and his cynical sense of superiority serves as a type of self-prtoection. Thus, Holden's alienation is the source of what little stability he has in his life.

He never addresses his own emotions directly...He desperately needs human contact and love, but his protective wall of bitterness prevents him from looking for such interaction. Alienation is both the source of Holden's strength and the source of his problems.

Okay. Today I was scammed at Target. I'm out and about Roseville buying Renuka her lovely birthday present bag, tissue, and card...the store is going to close in about five minutes and I want to go home. So I bring my basket to the checkout. Now, I'm a firm believer that attidude really can make an impact on things. Even such things as little over the checkout conversations. So automatically the guy asks me how I am. Okay. Only okay? Yeah I'm good. Things he does too much: cares and smiles slyly: at the same time. Aack I think to myself. I want to get out of here. This is a rubbernecking type of guy (lol, Chelsea)So I'm like yeah, okay get on with it...12 something is the total I hand him a twenty b/c i'm too lazy to charge and I don't want him to know my name b/c of his smilingasshole weird aura---of course i'm the analytical crazy one, but still, it's a subconscious way of thinking that I have i guess...so yeah, he counts out the change (mocking me I'm sure of after the discovery i made!)into my hand and I grab the bag, and put the money in my wallet as I walk out with my mom. The bag sits by my white high tops on our way home. We get home, I look into the bag for the card and the receipt. they are no where to be found. I run out to the car again. They aren't on the ground. I go back, empty the bag and search aimlessly for the receipt and card. The guy charged me for everything. But the card wasn't there, and the receipt was missing as well. I called 411 to get that sleazy target's number. But they were closed dammit. So yeah, I'm calling their asses tomorrow. And I'm gonna raise hell! Because this is a card and a reciept we're talkin about! I've been scammed. the worst part is, is all the foreshadowing. The overcharging at Fresh Choice, the forgetting to check the reciept before signing it in Copelands....all leading up to this hard learned lesson.


i can't believe I wrote that much about target.

Yes. It was fun, a lot of fun. But it's kind of difficult to have different groups of people b/c you can't be with everyone at once. I've gained a lot of experience, and had I known what I know now before I think that the t-shirt designs, and other things may have worked out better (organization? a plan? pshhh noooo....my bedroom, my bathroom, and my library...room, are a mess) Anyways, it was fun, and I am sooooo lucky, that I can't even complain. I had so much fun in fact, that my voice has left me, and I am left to converse in whispers. So, this morning I'm in bed watching Gene Hackman's biography on the biography channel, eating apple jacks, Sam's cookies, Chelsea's caramel-chocolate, reading the notes and cards I didn't have time to last night, and looking and reading the pretty magazine page that Haley gave me...thank you.

so now without my voice, I will go back to bed, study for history, and later, attempt the cleaning of my house that was so nicely left to me in a state of...uhhh...messiness.
